<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="187" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="187">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="187">
Phylogenetically, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. He &amp; J. X. Deng" authorityYear="2021" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Pleosporaceae" genus="Alternaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Alternaria divaricatae" order="Pleosporales" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="divaricatae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">Alternaria divaricatae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms a distinct clade in section 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meier, Drechsler &amp; E.D.Eddy" authorityYear="1922" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Pleosporaceae" genus="Alternaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="" order="Pleosporales" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="section" section="Radicina">Radicina</taxonomicName>
, which appears to be sister to a clade including 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. petroselini" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="petroselini">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. petroselini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. selini" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="selini">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. selini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. vulgarae" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="vulgarae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. vulgarae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Phylogenetic tree based on the combined gene sequences of ITS, TEF 1, GAPDH, and RPB 2. The Bayesian posterior probabilities&gt; 0.70 (PP), maximum likelihood and maximum parsimony bootstrap support values&gt; 70 (BS) are given at the nodes (PP / BS). Examined strains are in bold." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.78.64853.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/530235" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">1</figureCitation>
). Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. divaricatae" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="divaricatae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. divaricatae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was different from 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. petroselini" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="petroselini">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. petroselini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. selini" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="selini">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. selini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. vulgarae" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="vulgarae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. vulgarae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by producing smaller conidia (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="T2" captionText="Table 2. Morphological comparison of the present species and other Altenraria species in section Altenraria Radicina" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/4CE987FE318663FED09E9F2ABF20170C" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" tableUuid="4CE987FE318663FED09E9F2ABF20170C">2</tableCitation>
) and special sporulation from apex or geniculate loci of lateral or apical of aerial hyphae. Moreover, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. chlamydosporifera" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="chlamydosporifera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. chlamydosporifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. glehniae" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="glehniae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. glehniae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. smyrnii" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="smyrnii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. smyrnii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
grouped together and clustered as a sister clade with 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. divaricatae" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="divaricatae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. divaricatae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. petroselini" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="petroselini">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. petroselini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. selini" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="selini">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. selini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. vulgarae" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="vulgarae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. vulgarae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Phylogenetic tree based on the combined gene sequences of ITS, TEF 1, GAPDH, and RPB 2. The Bayesian posterior probabilities&gt; 0.70 (PP), maximum likelihood and maximum parsimony bootstrap support values&gt; 70 (BS) are given at the nodes (PP / BS). Examined strains are in bold." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.78.64853.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/530235" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">1</figureCitation>
). Obviously, the conidia of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. divaricatae" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="divaricatae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. divaricatae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was smaller than 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. smyrnii" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="smyrnii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. smyrnii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="T2" captionText="Table 2. Morphological comparison of the present species and other Altenraria species in section Altenraria Radicina" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/4CE987FE318663FED09E9F2ABF20170C" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" tableUuid="4CE987FE318663FED09E9F2ABF20170C">2</tableCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. divaricatae" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="divaricatae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. divaricatae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could be also easily differentiated from 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. chlamydosporifera" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="chlamydosporifera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. chlamydosporifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the lack of chlamydospores in culture (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2019.05.001" author="Marin-Felix, Y" journalOrPublisher="Studies in Mycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" pagination="1 - 124" refId="B20" refString="Marin-Felix, Y, Hernandez-Restrepo, M, Iturrieta-Gonzalez, I, Garcia, D, Gene, J, Groenewald, JZ, Cai, L, Chen, Q, Quaedvlieg, W, Schumacher, RK, Taylor, PWJ, Ambers, C, Bonthond, G, Edwards, J, Krueger-Hadfield, SA, Luangsa-ard, JJ, Morton, L, Moslemi, A, Sandoval-Denis, M, Tan, YP, Thangavel, R, Vaghefi, N, Cheewangkoon, R, Crous, PW, 2019. Genera of phytopathogenic fungi: GOPHY 3. Studies in Mycology 94: 1 - 124, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2019.05.001" title="Genera of phytopathogenic fungi: GOPHY 3." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2019.05.001" volume="94" year="2019">Marin-Felix et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
). Meanwhile, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. glehniae" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="glehniae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. glehniae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was distinguished from 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. divaricatae" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="divaricatae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. divaricatae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its single conidium on apex of conidiophore (there was no geniculate sporulation loci) and production of secondary conidium (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.397.2.4" author="Tao, YQ" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" pagination="169 - 176" refId="B33" refString="Tao, YQ, Jia, GG, Aung, SLL, Wu, QL, Lu, HX, Deng, JX, 2019. Multigene phylogeny and morphology of Alternaria reveal a novel species and a new record in china. Phytotaxa 397 (2): 169 - 176, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.397.2.4" title="Multigene phylogeny and morphology of Alternaria reveal a novel species and a new record in china." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.397.2.4" volume="397" year="2019">Tao et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
). In addition, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. radicina" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="radicina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. radicina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. carotiincultae" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="species" species="carotiincultae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="187">A. carotiincultae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were distinguished from present species by distant phylogenetic relationship in section 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="187" rank="section" section="Radicina">Radicina</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
